{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018ufrM5hCiCdoivhifpZ6CT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. Changes 2 and 3 from the improvement plan have already been implemented in recent commits.\n2. Change 1 (dedup) was explicitly reverted and replaced with the \"keep shorter\" logic, and the user says NOT to change it.\n\nSo the question is: with only Changes 2 and 3 implemented (and Change 1 NOT implemented), can we fix the 4 failing cases?\n\nThe improvement plan assumes all 3 changes work together. Change 1 (dedup) was supposed to be the main fix for:\n- ARAYES SHRAK\n- Baked Eggs with Feta...\n\n\n- SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS...\n\nWithout Change 1, these three cases likely still fail. Change 3 (baseScore threshold) was supposed to fix the FINNISH case.\n\nThe unit tests all pass because they're mock-based and test general logic like \"joins multi-line title\" or \"picks title over section header\", but the 6 failing/passing cases in `results.txt` come from running the actual title-loop with real recipe texts and real embeddings. So I need to find changes I can make without touching the dedup block to fix the 4 failing cases.\n\nThe user's constraint is clear: keep the dedup logic exactly as-is with the \"shorter wins\" behavior. But the improvement plan identifies the dedup as causing 3 of the 4 failures, which creates a contradiction—I can't fix those cases without changing the very thing I'm forbidden to modify.\n\nLet me trace through what Changes 2 and 3 actually accomplish without touching dedup. Change 3 helps FINNISH by adjusting the threshold calculation. Change 2 adds structural awareness to heading detection, which gives SAFFRON a boost, but the dedup still strips it down to the shorter partial match. So realistically, only FINNISH might pass with these changes alone—ARAYES, Baked Eggs, and SAFFRON remain broken because the dedup removes their longer, correct titles in favor of shorter substrings.\n\nNow I'm realizing the constraint about not inverting to keep the longer is directly contradicting what the improvement plan suggests. The plan says to keep longer when tied, but the constraint explicitly forbids that and warns it breaks tests, specifically the Pierogi Ruskie case which needs shorter to win. So the constraint is protecting against a regression that would fail existing tests. Looking at the \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\" candidate, I need to check if it passes the hard filters—specifically whether `looksLikeIngredient` would catch it as an ingredient line rather than a title, since it contains quantity information mixed with the dish name. Refining the deduplication logic...\n\nWith the stricter condition, the longer entry only gets removed if the shorter one has a strictly higher score—if they're tied, the longer one survives. So \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\" would stay in the results since both entries would end up with equal scores.\n\nBut wait, I need to check if \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki\" is even in the candidate list to begin with. Let me trace through the line splitting: the input gets broken into \"Składniki\", \"Pierogi Ruskie\", \"200g mąki\", \"3 ziemniaki\". Then I'm checking the garbled text detection—looking at whether \"Składniki\" passes the vowel ratio check after stripping non-ASCII characters.\n\nSince \"Składniki\" isn't garbled, the burst-finding loop exits immediately at position 0, so burstEnd stays at 0 and the loop starts processing from the first line.\n\nNow I'm checking which candidates pass the filters—\"Składniki\" itself clears the hard checks and isn't garbled, so it qualifies as a candidate. When I try joining it with \"Pierogi Ruskie\" across two lines, that also passes the filters, but this is where the complexity emerges: the proposed change would break the Polish test because shorter lines like \"Pierogi Ruskie\" would get filtered out incorrectly.\n\nI'm realizing the issue with measurement detection—\"200g mąki\" doesn't match the English measurement patterns in the code, so it passes the hard filters even though it contains a quantity. The whole string \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\" starts with a letter, not a number, so it technically passes the initial check, but the measurement component within it isn't being caught properly.\n\nThis means Change 1 would keep the longer variant on a score tie, which breaks the Polish test case because the deduplication logic would fail to remove the more detailed version in favor of the cleaner title.\n\nSo I'm stuck: I can't modify the dedup without breaking tests, but Change 1 (which fixes most of the real-world failures) requires changing it. The user asked me to execute the improvement plan, but maybe they're expecting a different approach that solves the same four failing cases without touching the dedup logic.\n\nLet me reconsider what's actually happening with cases like \"ARAYES SHRAK\" — it gets removed because \"ARAYES\" is shorter and passes the hard filters, so the dedup keeps only the substring.\n\nI could try adding a penalty for single-word candidates that are substrings of longer candidates, or give multi-word candidates a scoring bonus to make them more competitive. These would sit outside the dedup block and might help without changing the core dedup behavior.\n\nBut I'm realizing the real tension here: the improvement plan wants longer candidates to win on ties, yet that breaks the Polish test. Maybe I can use the scored version instead of raw scores in the dedup logic while keeping the shorter-wins behavior, which would be different from what the plan actually proposes.\n\nLet me trace through the ARAYES case more carefully. \"ARAYES\" is shorter than \"ARAYES SHRAK\", so if I keep shorter-wins-on-ties, then \"ARAYES\" would be removed only if \"ARAYES SHRAK\" has a strictly higher score. The question is whether \"ARAYES SHRAK\" actually gets enough bonus points from the structural heading and all-caps bonuses to outweigh \"ARAYES\".\n\nSince \"ARAYES\" is a single word, it doesn't qualify for the `firstStructuralHeading` bonus (which requires at least 2 words with 4+ alpha letters each). \"ARAYES SHRAK\" does qualify, so it gets both the all-caps bonus and the structural heading bonus, giving it a 0.10 point advantage over \"ARAYES\" even if they have the same raw score. This means \"ARAYES SHRAK\" will always rank higher and \"ARAYES\" gets filtered out. The current deduplication logic simply removes any item if there's a shorter item whose text is a substring of it—it doesn't consider scores at all. So \"ARAYES SHRAK\" gets filtered out because \"ARAYES\" is shorter and contained within it.\n\nI could potentially prevent this by ensuring \"ARAYES\" doesn't pass the score threshold in the first place, but that's difficult to control with mock embeddings in the unit tests versus real embeddings in the title-loop tests. Let me check if changes 2 and 3 from the improvement plan are actually implemented correctly, since change 1 conflicts with the existing constraint. 2 and 3 are already implemented, so I'd need to skip Change 1 due to the constraint and report the conflict to the user. But maybe I can work around this—what if I add a penalty for single-word candidates to prevent \"ARAYES\" from passing the threshold in the first place, rather than modifying the dedup logic itself?\n\nActually, a cleaner approach might be to insert a score-based dedup pass before the protected substring-removal block. That way the first pass handles the scoring logic from Change 1, and then the protected block runs afterward without being violated.\n\nBut there's a problem: if the first pass removes the shorter candidate when the longer one scores higher, the protected block would still see both in `selected` and remove the longer one anyway, undoing the work. The logic only removes the shorter candidate when it has strictly higher score, so I need to think through whether this ordering actually solves the issue.\n\nLet me trace through the actual scenario: \"ARAYES SHRAK\" scores higher than \"ARAYES\" because of the bonus, so Change 1 would remove \"ARAYES\" first. Then when the protected block runs, \"ARAYES\" is already gone, so \"ARAYES SHRAK\" survives. This might actually work—let me check if it holds up with the Polish example too.\n\nFor \"Pierogi Ruskie\" versus the longer variant, both get the same raw score with no bonuses applied, so Change 1 would incorrectly remove the shorter one. But wait, looking at the actual test data, the mock embeddings give different scores for these two strings, which changes the calculation entirely. I'm checking whether \"200g\" and other mixed alphanumeric tokens pass the garbled word filter by examining vowel ratios and word structure, making sure none of the tokens look like corrupted text.\n\nThe real issue is that the mock embedding function returns identical vectors for both \"Pierogi Ruskie\" and the longer candidate string, which is causing the test to fail.\n\nIn actual embeddings, a clean title would score higher than the same title mixed with ingredient text because the embedding gets diluted by the extra content. The deduplication logic relies on this real-world behavior, but the mock doesn't capture it—it treats any string containing the title words as equivalent. For ARAYES specifically, this becomes problematic because the join operation creates a candidate that the mock can't distinguish from the original title.\n\nThe core issue is that the dedup can't tell the difference between a noisy suffix (where we should keep the shorter version) and a legitimate title continuation (where we should keep the longer one). The structural bonus from the heading hierarchy would solve this, but that's not an option given the constraints. So I need to explore alternative approaches to handle these edge cases.\n\nOne possibility is to add a pre-dedup filter that removes single-word candidates when they're exact prefixes of a multi-word `firstStructuralHeading`. This way, \"ARAYES\" wouldn't compete with \"ARAYES SHRAK\" during dedup—the longer, more complete title would survive naturally. I'm sketching out the logic for this filter now...\n\nWriting filter logic...\n\nBut looking at SAFFRON, the partial candidate is already multi-word, so this prefix-removal approach wouldn't help there.\n\nLet me reconsider the whole strategy—instead of trying to fix the dedup logic, what if I filter out candidates that are proper substrings of the first structural heading before the threshold check even happens? That way I'd remove things like \"ARAYES\" if it's a prefix of the heading, and handle the SAFFRON case differently.\n\nImplementing a pre-dedup filter...\n\nWriting the filter logic...\n\nNow I'm testing this against the examples: for ARAYES, the filter removes the shorter \"ARAYES\" prefix since it's contained in \"ARAYES SHRAK\", leaving only the full title. For SAFFRON, the same logic applies—shorter prefixes get filtered out before deduplication runs, so only the complete structural heading survives.\n\nBut Baked Eggs doesn't have an all-caps structural heading, so this filter doesn't help there. I need a different approach to handle that case.\n\nThe real issue is that the partial title \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" scores nearly as high as the full version with \"& Coriander\" added. In theory, the complete title should rank higher in embeddings since it contains all the information, but I can't rely on that scoring difference being large enough to overcome the deduplication logic.\n\nI could try adding a length bonus to favor longer candidates, but that might break the dedup strategy elsewhere. Or I could extend the structural heading concept to mixed-case titles, but that gets complicated. Looking back at Failure 2, the real problem is that after the join gets eliminated by dedup, both remaining candidates—the partial first line and the orphaned \"& Coriander\"—score too low to pass the threshold, leaving nothing to return. Hmm, the result is `undefined` (empty string), not \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\". So the partial ALSO fails the threshold? That's interesting.\n\nWait, the plan says \"Both may score too low\" - maybe in practice the partial scores just above threshold (at position 0) and the full join (at position 0 since they both start at line 0) also scores... Actually both \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" and \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" start at the same position (line 0), so they have the same position factor.\n\nBut the result was \"\" (empty string), meaning NO candidate passed. I think what's happening is that the threshold is calculated from all candidates before dedup, so if the full join has the highest baseScore, the partial and \"& Coriander\" variant might both fall below the 0.7 × bestBaseScore threshold even though they have very similar embeddings to the full title. I'm realizing the threshold filter runs before dedup, so the partial \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" likely passes and survives dedup since it's shorter than the full version. The fragment \"& Coriander\" alone probably scores too low to pass the threshold. But the improvement plan was written before the recent code changes, so maybe the current implementation with Changes 2 and 3 already fixes some of these cases—I should test the title-loop again to see if FINNISH and SAFFRON are actually resolved now.\n\nFor the remaining issues, I could add a pre-dedup filter to preserve candidates with firstStructuralHeading prefixes (which would help ARAYES and SAFFRON), but Baked Eggs is trickier since it has no structural heading. The only real fix without major refactoring would be to boost the score of longer, more complete candidates—maybe through a length bonus or a continuation-awareness bonus that rewards candidates that feel like complete phrases rather than fragments. I'm getting bogged down in complexity here. Let me step back and focus on what's actually pragmatic: I've already implemented Changes 2 and 3, so I should add the pre-dedup filter for firstStructuralHeading prefixes to handle the ARAYES and SAFFRON cases, then verify whether this breaks any existing unit tests. The key thing to check is whether filtering out candidates that start with structural heading prefixes would cause issues with the Polish test case. With \"CHOCOLATE CAKE\" as the structural heading, I'm checking which candidates get filtered out by the prefix logic. The heading itself passes through since it matches exactly, but \"CHOCOLATE CAKE Ingredients\" gets caught because the filter checks if the heading starts with the candidate string (not the other way around), so it gets removed. Now I'm working through \"Ingredients\" to see if it also gets filtered.\n\nFor the \"ARAYES SHRAK\" case, I need to verify the same logic applies with that heading.\n\nFor \"CHOCOLATE CAKE\", the candidate \"CHOCOLATE CAKE Ingredients\" doesn't get filtered out because the first structural heading is shorter than the candidate text, so it can't be a prefix match.\n\nNow I'm checking the multi-line title test case to see how the joining logic handles text split across lines. Checking whether \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" is a prefix of the full title \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" to see if the deduplication logic would catch this case correctly.\n\nFor the Finnish case, I need to verify that \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" and \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" are distinct titles that wouldn't be filtered as duplicates since neither is a prefix of the other. The mismatch at \"milk\" means \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" won't be removed by the pre-dedup filter. The real fix for the FINNISH case comes from the threshold adjustment based on baseScore, which is already in place. Now I'm wondering if the pre-dedup filter itself could cause issues—like if \"ARAYES\" gets filtered out while \"ARAYES SHRAK\" is also removed for a different reason, since `firstStructuralHeading` is computed from all candidates regardless of whether they pass the threshold.\n\nIn practice though, if \"ARAYES SHRAK\" qualifies as the first structural heading, it probably scores well enough to pass the threshold anyway. I think the pre-dedup filter is solid, but I should consider whether it should only apply when both candidates are in the selected list.\n\nChecking if both candidates are in selected... I'm verifying the word boundary logic with some examples—\"arayes\" and \"arayes shrak\" works because the space after \"arayes\" triggers the match, and \"saffron wheat buns with quark\" correctly identifies the \"/\" as a word boundary. The filter should only remove strict prefixes that end at word boundaries, not partial word matches.\n\nNow I'm planning the implementation: add a pre-dedup filter that removes candidates matching the firstStructuralHeading at word boundaries, but only if the firstStructuralHeading itself passed the threshold. This goes before the existing dedup block and should resolve the ARAYES and SAFFRON cases, while the FINNISH case is already handled by an earlier change. The Baked Eggs case has no structural heading to work with, so I'm reconsidering whether there's anything else I can do there.\n\nLooking at the Baked Eggs scenario more carefully—the full title has the highest score, so the threshold becomes 0.7 times that score, which means the partial version would need to score at least that high to survive. Since it's shorter and likely scores lower, it should get filtered out by the existing dedup logic anyway.\n\nFor the other cases, I'm stuck between a few options: raising the threshold could help but risks breaking other things, or making the \"keep shorter\" rule conditional on a substantial score improvement—but that would require modifying the dedup block, which I'm trying to avoid. Looking at the full picture, the pre-dedup filter handles ARAYES SHRAK, Change 3 already fixes FINNISH, and the Baked Eggs case might just be inherently difficult without rearchitecting how scoring works. uses bestBaseScore * 0.7)\n4. SAFFRON: Can fix with pre-dedup filter (removes \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" as prefix of firstStructuralHeading)\n\nSo I can potentially get from 33.3% (2/6) to 66.7% (4/6) with just the pre-dedup filter (fixes 2 more cases), assuming FINNISH is also fixed by Change 3 (giving 5/6 or 83.3%).\n\nActually, let me re-read the current code... The current code has `threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestBaseScore * 0.7)`. The improvement plan for Change 3 mentioned 0.8 → 0.7 as the multiplier. And the plan originally said 0.7 was the safe choice. This is already in the code.\n\nSo with the current code state, Changes 2 and 3 are already implemented, but Change 1 remains blocked by the constraint. That means without the dedup change, three cases could still fail—ARAYES, Baked Eggs, and SAFFRON—though the pre-dedup filter would handle two of them. Looking at the projected outcomes, ARAYES SHRAK and FINNISH should pass, but Baked Eggs would still fail.\n\nWait, let me reconsider whether Baked Eggs actually fails with the current threshold. The failure description mentions that after dedup, both the partial first line and orphaned \"& Coriander\" might score similarly, but I should verify if the threshold change alone could resolve this.\n\nLooking at the code flow more carefully: the threshold filter runs before dedup, so it passes all candidates scoring above the threshold first, then dedup removes the longer duplicates. This means \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" would survive the threshold check before being compared against the longer version during dedup.\n\nThe key insight is that with the new threshold calculation using `0.7 * bestBaseScore` instead of the old `0.8 * bestScore`, the threshold is actually lower. Since the partial and full join have similar embedding scores, the partial should comfortably pass the threshold — it's roughly equal to bestBaseScore, which is well above 0.7 times that value.\n\nThis means \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" would survive as the result instead of an empty string, but that's still not the expected full title. The pre-dedup filter approach seems like the right direction to explore, even if it doesn't fully solve the Baked Eggs case yet. I'm exploring whether I can add scoring bonuses to prefer full joins—maybe detecting continuation patterns like \"& [word]\" endings or checking if a candidate is the longest available option from the same position. But these approaches feel too ad-hoc. I think I should stick with the pre-dedup filter strategy, which is cleaner and more principled, even if it means accepting that the Baked Eggs case won't be resolved perfectly. Let me consider one more angle: adjusting the scoring to give a small bonus for mixed content.\n\nActually, I just realized there's a way to fix this—I can add the \"longer wins when equal score\" logic before the protected dedup block runs. If I implement a pre-dedup pass that removes shorter candidates when a longer one has an equal or better score, then the protected dedup block won't interfere with cases like \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce.\"\n\nThe question is whether the full join's score would actually be >= the partial's score. Since both have the same position and no structural bonuses, it comes down to rawScore. If the full join's rawScore is at least as good as the partial's, the pre-dedup pass removes the shorter one and we get the right result. But if the partial is more semantically similar to the reference, it won't get removed in the pre-dedup pass, and then the protected dedup will remove the full join instead—which means we'd still end up with the partial.\n\nFor the Polish test case, both strings return the same embedding scores in the mock, giving them equal rawScores. The pre-dedup pass would remove the shorter \"Pierogi Ruskie\" since the longer one has a score >= it. That breaks the test. But in reality, the shorter string would have a higher embedding score because it's more semantically similar to the reference, which would prevent this issue.\n\nThe core problem is that my mock embeddings treat any text containing the title keywords identically, ignoring noise. So dedup logic based on \"longer wins on tie\" fails with the mock. I could adjust the mock to differentiate exact matches from noisy ones, but the user said not to modify tests. Let me reconsider whether the scoring itself already handles this—with real embeddings, the clean title would get higher titleSim and lower noise penalties, resulting in a higher rawScore that would prevent the incorrect removal.\n\nLooking at the specific cases: \"Pierogi Ruskie\" embeds cleanly with high titleSim, while the version with ingredients gets penalized by noiseSim, so the clean one wins outright. \"ARAYES SHRAK\" gets both a higher embedding score and a structural bonus as the first heading, beating \"ARAYES\" decisively. For \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" versus the truncated version, the embeddings are nearly identical and neither has structural bonuses, so this is where the tie-breaking logic would matter.\n\nI've been overthinking this. I'll implement a pre-dedup filter that removes candidates that are proper word-boundary prefixes of the first structural heading when it's selected—this handles ARAYES and SAFFRON without touching the protected dedup block. The Baked Eggs case will remain unfixed since addressing it would require modifying the dedup logic itself, which I'm avoiding. This approach should resolve most of the issues while staying within the constraints.\n\nNow I'm adding the filtering logic to `title-extractor.ts`...\n\nWriting the prefix filter... I'm testing the logic against specific examples to verify it handles word boundaries correctly—like ensuring \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" gets filtered out when the first structural heading is \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\", and \"ARAYES\" gets removed when paired with \"ARAYES SHRAK\". For the Polish test case with \"Pierogi Ruskie\", there are no all-caps candidates, so the first structural heading remains undefined and the filter doesn't apply.\n\nNow checking the all-caps preservation test with \"CHOCOLATE CAKE\"—the candidates would include the full heading and variations like \"CHOCOLATE CAKE Ingredients\", but since the first structural heading is shorter than any candidate with additional words, nothing gets removed. However, if \"CHOCOLATE\" alone were a candidate, it would match the beginning of \"chocolate cake\" and get filtered out, though that's not the case here. isTitle would be false for \"CHOCOLATE\" since it doesn't contain the full phrase \"chocolate cake\", giving it a negative score that fails the threshold, so it wouldn't be selected anyway. Now let me trace through the \"skips burst of short lines\" test to make sure the pre-dedup filter handles that case correctly too.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2011,"cache_read_input_tokens":37031,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2011},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a0a05f64-dc5e-4fd2-9d6c-8483fb711304","uuid":"aad1d66d-939d-4e76-8798-d3878b835998"}
