{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ChEi4aVtVYeV4RwJoGu1AZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the style conventions. Let me implement the fix:\n\n1. Extract the structural heading qualification logic into a helper function\n2. After finding the initial heading, look for a longer continuation-joined heading\n3. Update the comment on the pre-dedup filter to accurately state it fixes ARAYES and SAFFRON (once the firstStructuralHeading computation is fixed)\n4. Add a test for the ARAYES case\n\nLet me write the code change:\n\nCurrent code:\n```typescript\n  // Find the first ALL_CAPS candidate with ≥2 words where every significant word has ≥4 alpha letters.\n  // This structural signal identifies the first clean recipe title heading in cookbook scans.\n\n\n```\n\nNow I'm implementing the helper function that checks if a candidate qualifies as a structural heading by verifying it's all caps with at least 2 words, then filtering out insignificant tokens and ensuring each remaining word has enough alphabetic characters... Filtering out insignificant tokens and then checking that the remaining significant words each have at least 4 uppercase letters, then finding the first candidate that passes this structural heading test. If there's a continuation on the next line starting with punctuation like \"/\" or \"&\", I'm preferring the longer two-line join as the complete heading instead of stopping at the initial match. I'm verifying the logic works correctly across different cases—for \"ARAYES SHRAK\" it properly identifies the two-word phrase as the base heading and filters out the single-word variant, and I'm checking how it handles longer multi-word entries like \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS\" to ensure the continuation character matching works as expected. I've confirmed that the \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" entry gets properly deduplicated after removing the base heading. Now I'm checking the \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" case—it has a potential continuation with \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS,\" but since that remainder doesn't start with a structural separator like \"/\" or \"&\", it gets rejected, leaving just the base heading. Moving on to test \"CHOCOLATE CAKE\" to see if it has any valid longer candidates.\n\nI notice the \"CHOCOLATE CAKE Ingredients\" variant isn't all caps, so there's no valid continuation there. The pre-dedup filter should correctly remove \"CHOCOLATE\" as a standalone word since it scores too low to be in the selected set anyway. Before I move forward, I should add an explicit return type annotation to the `isStructuralHeading` helper function to comply with the style guide, even though it's internal.\n\nNow I'm checking the \"Baked Eggs\" case—since that title isn't all caps, it won't trigger the baseHeading logic, and without a structural heading, there's no continuation check or pre-dedup filtering. That's fine given the constraints. I'm also working through the ARAYES test case where an all-caps single-word prefix gets removed but the two-word join survives.\n\nWriting test case... I see the issue—with a rawScore of -0.4, \"ARAYES\" won't pass the threshold at all, so the test would pass for the wrong reason. I need to adjust the mock so both candidates score similarly, which means using just \"arayes\" as the titleWord so that \"ARAYES\" alone also gets a strong embedding match.\n\nWriting test case...\n\nWith this setup, \"ARAYES\" scores 0.88 total (0.8 raw + 0.08 caps bonus), while \"ARAYES SHRAK\" edges ahead at 0.98 with the additional 0.10 structural bonus for being the first structural heading, which properly tests that the dedup logic prefers the multi-word variant. Now I'm recalculating the base scores for each option—\"ARAYES\" comes to 0.88 while \"ARAYES SHRAK\" reaches 0.98—and using that higher score to set my threshold at 0.686, which filters out lower-scoring candidates.\n\nBoth options clear this threshold, so I'm moving into the deduplication phase where I need to identify the firstStructuralHeading. Since \"ARAYES\" is just a single word, it doesn't qualify, leaving \"ARAYES SHRAK\" as the primary heading to check against.\n\nWith the pre-dedup filter in place, I'm checking if the heading starts with \"arayes \" — and it does, so \"ARAYES\" gets filtered out before deduplication even runs, allowing \"ARAYES SHRAK\" to survive. Without that filter, the standard dedup logic kicks in: \"ARAYES\" is a substring of \"ARAYES SHRAK\" and shorter, so it would be kept instead, removing the longer phrase.\n\nThis test case properly validates the new filtering behavior, so I'm adding it to the suite.\n\nNow I'm considering whether to also add a test for the continuation-aware firstStructuralHeading logic I'm modifying, since that's part of the fix too. The SAFFRON-style case would need lines like \"SAFFRON\" followed by \"/ SPICE\" to test the slash continuation handling, but I need to think through what the actual test data should look like.\n\nWriting test case... I'm checking whether \"/ VARIATION B\" passes the hard filters and garbled text detection. The length is fine, but I need to verify the garbled check—it looks at whether words start with lowercase letters, and none of these do. I'm also calculating the vowel ratio to see if it indicates garbled text.\n\nSo \"/ VARIATION B\" doesn't trigger the garbled detection and passes the hard filters, but it scores very low as a candidate since it's not recognized as a title or header word, giving it a neutral probability that results in a negative raw score well below the threshold.\n\nNow I'm checking if \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" qualifies as a structural heading—it's all caps, has multiple words, and each significant word meets the character minimum, so it does. Then I'm looking for whether the longer variant \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / VARIATION B\" is a continuation of this base heading by checking if the lowercase version starts with the base heading text followed by a continuation character like \"/\" or \"&\", which it does. Now I'm calculating the final scores with bonuses applied—the first structural heading gets an extra boost, pushing its score to about 1.076 compared to 0.976 for the other variant. Since the best base score is 0.98, I'm setting the threshold at 0.686, and both candidates clear it. Moving into the deduplication filter, I'm checking against the first structural heading in lowercase to identify any near-duplicates.\n\nThe \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" entry gets filtered out because it's a substring match, leaving only the variation B heading and potentially \"Ingredients\" if it qualifies. The join operation confirms there are no shorter substrings in the selected results, so the test should pass with just the variation B heading remaining.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the ARAYES test case with both the pre-dedup filter and the continuation-extension logic in mind. Single-word headings like \"ARAYES\" don't qualify as structural, but \"ARAYES SHRAK\" with two words does, and I need to trace through how the scoring and filtering would handle this scenario.\n\nThe pre-dedup filter catches \"ARAYES SHRAK\" and removes the single-word \"ARAYES\" prefix, which is the key fix needed here—the continuation extension logic isn't actually required for this test to work correctly.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement the actual changes in the code, starting with replacing the structural heading detection logic with the two-step approach using the helper function.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8788,"cache_read_input_tokens":65611,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":8788},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a0a05f64-dc5e-4fd2-9d6c-8483